<div style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3); border-left: 5px solid white; border-right: 5px solid white; padding: 5px 3px; margin: 0.3em; text-align:left; font-size:25px;">  ✎ '''DESCRIPTION'''</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Thriftshop.webp|width=350px|caption=A section of Level 219, mimicking [[Level 53]].}}
{{Blurimage|file=Anotheremptyoffice.jpg|width=350px|caption=A section of Level 219, mimicking [[Level 4]].}}
'''Level 219''' has no standard appearance, as it varies depending on the method used to enter the level — it can override a target level's entrances and alter its appearance accordingly. For example, attempting to noclip in [[Level 0]] may inadvertently result in entering '''Level 219''' as opposed to [[Level 1]], causing '''Level 219''' to change itself based on Level 1's appearance.

In general, '''Level 219's''' environment is a set of vintage office spaces containing furniture and colored walls akin to that of its replicated level. The carpet always remains a musty, dull-ochre shade further saturated by the dingy fluorescent lights above. The walls are often aligned into display-esque areas as if to showcase the furniture within. These display areas often simulate the environment of the replicated level — on some occasions, even mimicking outposts in the level. Regardless of the simulated level's theme, analog clocks are common throughout '''Level 219,''' emitting a constant yet soft ticking noise in unison throughout the environment.

The time in '''Level 219''' constantly remains at the exact date of April 1st, 1993; additionally being the date which the level's discovery was first documented. Despite this, the passing of time in '''Level 219''' is entirely regular and nearly identical to that of [[The Frontrooms|Earth]]. Due to the level's dimensions interfering with the flow of time, '''Level 219''' is afflicted with an isolating effect that ensures wanderers are [[Phenomenon 15|alone]] and separated into distinct copies of the level.

'''Level 219''' holds a unique property which allows it to manifest objects according to the subconscious thinking of the wanderer within. At a wanderer's most susceptible moment, '''Level 219''' can create typical surprise-based joke contraptions to target them. These may involve methods such as shooting confetti at the target or creating plastic-wrap barriers; nonetheless, all manifested objects retain a theme of practical pranks which are used against the wanderer.

Speakers are hidden within the ventilation systems in the ceiling, which play standard sitcom laugh tracks after a wanderer is caught in a prank. How the speakers respond on time is unknown, though it is believed the level possesses a rudimentary form of sensory awareness. Consequently, it can transmit a response in the form of the aforementioned speaker tracks. This is not to say the level has sentience, however; only that it can respond to stimuli in a more advanced form.
<div style="background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3); border-left: 5px solid white; border-right: 5px solid white; padding: 5px 3px; margin: 0.3em; text-align:left; font-size:25px;">  ✎ '''ACTIVE LIFE'''</div>
<u><span style="font-size: 35px">VOODOO STATUES</span></u>
{{Blurimage|file=Vstatuescropped.jpg|width=350px|caption=A group of live Voodoo Statues in Level 219.}}
'''Voodoo Statues''' take the appearance of matte-white mannequins which are seldom stationed in '''Level 219's''' display areas. Bearing minimal details aside from major body parts, '''Voodoo Statues''' are either unclothed or bear attire similar to gear issued to members of various groups. They are typically seen in collections, which form still scenes in the display areas that demonstrate human activities in the Backrooms. '''Voodoo Statues''' are unable to move and are nourished through tubes in the ground of '''Level 219''' which deliver an off-grey sludge through the "esophagus" portions of the mannequin. These esophagi, spanning from the feet to the abdomen, use muscle contractions to transport fluid to the central digestion chamber. While little is known about how '''Voodoo Statues''' use energy outside of the digestion process, it is theorized that the mannequin appearance is merely a form of protective exterior for the entity.

A '''Voodoo Statue''' can exhibit various anomalous effects relating to the wanderer's senses only when in its living state. '''Voodoo Statues''' possess the ability to repeat the sensory inputs received by the wanderer in relation to the mannequin, causing extreme rates of disorientation when in close proximity. Whether this is intended to serve as a self-defense mechanism or not is debated, though it is known that other lifeforms cannot experience the effects — suggesting the properties may instead activate the required neurons in the viewer's mind.

